1d:["$","div",null,{"className":"markdown-container","children":[["$","h1","h1-0",{"children":"History of Automation: Part 1"}],"\n",["$","h2","h2-0",{"children":"Antiquity to the Industrial Revolution (300 BCE – 1900 CE)"}],"\n",["$","p","p-0",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Scope"}],": The mechanical origins of automation, early analog computers, and the birth of mathematical control theory."]}],"\n",["$","hr","hr-0",{}],"\n",["$","h2","h2-1",{"children":"1. The Ancient Era (300 BCE - 1600 CE)"}],"\n",["$","h3","h3-0",{"children":"~300 BCE: Ctesibius' Water Clock (Alexandria)"}],"\n",["$","p","p-1",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Event"}],": Ctesibius of Alexandria designs a water clock with a float-based feedback regulation system.",["$","br","br-0",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-1",{"children":"Significance"}],": First recorded closed-loop feedback mechanism; maintains constant water outflow despite input variations.",["$","br","br-1",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-2",{"children":"Modern Parallel"}],": Foundation of proportional control."]}],"\n",["$","h3","h3-1",{"children":"~100 BCE: The Antikythera Mechanism (Greece)"}],"\n",["$","p","p-2",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Event"}],": The creation of an intricate bronze, gear-driven device used to predict astronomical positions and eclipses decades in advance.\n",["$","strong","strong-1",{"children":"Significance"}],": Widely considered the world's first analog computer.\n",["$","strong","strong-2",{"children":"Impact"}],": Demonstrates that complex mathematical modeling of the physical world could be entirely automated through mechanical engineering, centuries before the digital age."]}],"\n",["$","h3","h3-2",{"children":"~50 CE: Hero of Alexandria's Programmable Automata"}],"\n",["$","p","p-3",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Event"}],": Hero invents wind-powered machines and theatrical automata driven by complex systems of ropes, weights, and pneumatics.\n",["$","strong","strong-1",{"children":"Significance"}],": One of the earliest examples of a machine following a predetermined \"program\" to perform a sequence of actions without human intervention during execution."]}],"\n",["$","h3","h3-3",{"children":"~1206: Al-Jazari's Programmable Automata (Persia)"}],"\n",["$","p","p-4",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Event"}],": Al-Jazari designs mechanical automata and control systems for water clocks.",["$","br","br-0",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-1",{"children":"Significance"}],": Early programmable machines; manipulates gears and cams to encode behavior.",["$","br","br-1",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-2",{"children":"Modern Parallel"}],": Predecessor to the Jacquard loom's punched card programming."]}],"\n",["$","h3","h3-4",{"children":"1601: Galileo's Pendulum Escapement"}],"\n",["$","p","p-5",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Event"}],": Galileo observes pendulum regularity; sketches escapement mechanism for clocks.",["$","br","br-0",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-1",{"children":"Significance"}],": Enables constant time measurement; escapement regulates energy release.",["$","br","br-1",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-2",{"children":"Impact"}],": Foundation of mechanical clock precision; enables timekeeping for navigation."]}],"\n",["$","hr","hr-1",{}],"\n",["$","h2","h2-2",{"children":"2. The Industrial Revolution (1788 - 1900)"}],"\n",["$","h3","h3-5",{"children":"1788: James Watt's Centrifugal Governor"}],"\n",["$","p","p-6",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Event"}],": Watt develops a governor mechanism for the steam engine; rotating balls lift against springs as engine speed increases, proportionally reducing throttle.",["$","br","br-0",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-1",{"children":"Significance"}],": The first widespread closed-loop feedback control; enables stable factory operation at constant speeds.","$L26","\n","$L27",": Proportional control: (u(t) \\propto e(t))."]}],"\n","$L28","\n","$L29","\n","$L2a","\n","$L2b","\n","$L2c","\n","$L2d","\n","$L2e","\n","$L2f","\n","$L30","\n","$L31"]}]
26:["$","br","br-1",{}]
27:["$","strong","strong-2",{"children":"Mathematical Formulation"}]
28:["$","h3","h3-6",{"children":"1801: Joseph-Marie Jacquard's Programmable Loom"}]
29:["$","p","p-7",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Event"}],": Jacquard loom uses punched cards to control thread selection patterns.",["$","br","br-0",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-1",{"children":"Significance"}],": The first programmable manufacturing machine; patterns encoded externally, interpreted mechanically.",["$","br","br-1",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-2",{"children":"Modern Connection"}],": Punched cards remained the primary computer input method until the 1970s."]}]
2a:["$","h3","h3-7",{"children":"1837: Charles Babbage & Ada Lovelace's Analytical Engine"}]
2b:["$","p","p-8",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Event"}],": Babbage designs a mechanical general-purpose computer. Ada Lovelace publishes the first algorithm intended to be carried out by such a machine (calculating Bernoulli numbers).\n",["$","strong","strong-1",{"children":"Significance"}],": The conceptual birth of software separating from hardware. Lovelace recognized that the machine could manipulate any symbols (like music or logic), not just numbers, forecasting the true nature of modern computing."]}]
2c:["$","h3","h3-8",{"children":"1861-1876: Telegraph & Early Electrical Automation"}]
2d:["$","p","p-9",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Event"}],": Telegraph systems use electrical signals for long-distance communication; relay circuits enable switching.",["$","br","br-0",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-1",{"children":"Significance"}],": Introduces electrical actuation and logical switching.",["$","br","br-1",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-2",{"children":"Modern Parallel"}],": Foundation of digital logic and electrical control systems."]}]
2e:["$","h3","h3-9",{"children":"1868: James Clerk Maxwell's \"On Governors\""}]
2f:["$","p","p-10",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Event"}],": The brilliant physicist publishes a paper analyzing the mathematical stability of Watt's centrifugal governor using differential equations.\n",["$","strong","strong-1",{"children":"Significance"}],": This is widely considered the true, formal birth of Control Theory as an academic and mathematical discipline. He proved mathematically ",["$","em","em-0",{"children":"why"}]," and ",["$","em","em-1",{"children":"when"}]," a feedback system becomes unstable (hunting or oscillating), moving automation from trial-and-error engineering into rigorous mathematics."]}]
30:["$","hr","hr-2",{}]
